Security review: Helmet CSP, confirmation-gate audit, localhost re-audit

CSP (item #3):
- gateway/src/index.ts: connectSrc ["'self'", "*"] -> ["'self'"]; the
  dashboard is same-origin only (relative API base, no external subresources,
  no browser WebSocket), so 'self' is exact. upgradeInsecureRequests kept off
  (plain HTTP on the LAN). Added comments explaining both choices.
- tests/smoke-test.sh: new rheader helper; Phase 1 asserts connect-src is
  'self' and carries no permissive '*' (16 -> 18 checks).

Confirmation-gate "local requester" audit:
- No active vulnerability: the gate never grants on source IP/loopback, and
  approval is reachable only via the auth-gated POST /api/confirmations/:id/
  approve (no bridge or WebSocket path).
- gateway/src/services/confirmation-gate.ts: corrected the approve() docstring,
  which still claimed approval was safe because the server "binds to 127.0.0.1"
  — false since the LAN patch. Now states the bearer token is the trust
  boundary. Comment-only; no behavioral change.

Hardcoded localhost re-audit:
- Audited all 127.0.0.1/localhost source references for stale trust-boundary
  assumptions. Two findings, both fixed:
- gateway/src/api/routes.ts: corrected the file-header comment that claimed
  "/api/* is unauthenticated and that's acceptable because we bind to
  127.0.0.1" — false on both counts now; describes the real model.
- gateway/src/bridges/telegram.ts + index.ts: the Telegram bridge's in-process
  HTTP self-calls to /api/* sent no bearer token, so they would 401 under the
  now-default auth (regression from the auth work, breaking /export, /files,
  /clean, /speak, pause). Added TelegramBridge.apiHeaders() to attach the token
  from AUTHORCLAW_AUTH_TOKEN (omitted when auth disabled) across all 6 calls;
  the index.ts /export self-call uses this.authToken. Loopback-skip-auth was
  rejected (would reinstate the localhost trust boundary).

